ce:section.ce:para:
In order to further study the NRR reaction mechanism of catalysts, we performed electrochemical in situ ATR-SERAS and i-t tests in a saturated electrolyte with continuous N2 bubbling at −0.4 V vs. RHE. Fig. 7
                         shows the in-situ ATR-SIRAS spectra of ZrO2 and 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 and the NRR reaction pathway. Fig. 7a and c show the full spectra of ZrO2 and 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750, respectively. Fig. 7b and d are magnified images of the full spectra in Fig. 7a and c, respectively, aiming to study the visible spectra of N-related intermediates in the NRR to NH3 process. As the i-t test progressed, some IR spectra (Table 5
                        ), which are typical of N-related intermediates, became more evident with the elapse of the i-t test time. As shown in Fig. 7d, 1120 cm−1 belongs to the N–N stretch vibration, and its intensity becomes increasingly evident with increasing reaction time, which indicates that the N  N bond on the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 is broken [73]. The corresponding band of ZrO2 appears red-shifted (Fig. 7b), which indicates that the adsorption strength of the N–N intermediate on the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 is stronger than that of ZrO2. During the subsequent hydrogenation of the adsorbed N-related intermediates, NH2 intermediates are visible on the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 and ZrO2. Obviously, compared with ZrO2, the NH2 swing band and H–N–H bending band of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 are blue-shifted, indicating that the adsorption of NH2 intermediates onto the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 is stronger as well [74]. Therefore, according to the in-situ ATR-SEIRAS spectroscopy results, compared to pure ZrO2, the 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 catalyst with surface oxygen vacancies has a stronger adsorption capacity for N-related intermediates in the catalytic process of NRR. Furthermore, the broadband centered at 3375 cm−1 is assigned to N–H stretching [75]. Considering the existence of multiple N2Hy (1 ≤ y ≤ 4) intermediates and negligible N2H4 generation (Fig. 4e), the NRR mechanism on the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 catalyst should follow the association-alternating pathway (Fig. 7e) [76]. In the process of association alternation pathway, because the 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750 catalyst itself has strong N2 adsorption characteristics and effectively limits the accessibility of protons. So N2 molecules will be better close to the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750, which preferentially adsorbed by surface oxygen vacancies and Zr sites to activate N  N bonds. Then, the proton-ligation attack activates N  N to generate the –NN–H bond. Subsequently, with further hydrogenation of another proton, a -H-NN–H bond is formed, which is then converted to -H-NNH2 by electron transfer and continued hydrogenation. Finally, with the continuous attack of protons, NH3 is generated on the surface of 1-ZrO2/CQDs-750, and the NRR reaction occurs in 0.1 M Na2SO4 electrolyte.
